. And there are signs the new diversity strains community life. Yet in both countries, public opinion is running irreversibly in favour of tolerance. That augurs well for the future – and suggests a British Obama cannot be ruled out.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMinoritiesxPolitical activity. 0aMinoritieszGreat BritainxSocial conditions. 0aMinoritieszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aRace relations. 0aSegregation. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh  aAfrican Americans.  aBritish Obama.  acollaborative research.  acommunity life.  adiversity.  ainjustice.  aminorities.  apublic opinion.  arich world.  atolerance.1 aClark, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFieldhouse, Edward, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFieldhouse, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPutnam, Robert D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPutnam, Robert D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779281540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847792815423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847792815/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles